lt.andrikonis.penkiolika

Class ServerHandler

  • java.lang.Object
    • lt.andrikonis.penkiolika.ServerHandler
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    com.sun.net.httpserver.HttpHandler

    public class ServerHandler
extends java.lang.Object
implements com.sun.net.httpserver.HttpHandler
    Fifteen ("Penkiolika") game request handler. For a game description see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/15_puzzle. This handler listens to the following requests:
    • POST request to /penkiolika/game/ - creates a new game and returns it. Returns HTTP status 201 on success.
    • GET request to /penkiolika/game/<id> - returns an existing game. Returns HTTP status 200 on success and 404 if the game is not found.
    • PATCH request to /penkiolika/game/<id> - orders a server to make a move in the specified game. A move is specified in JSON using this syntax: {"move":"left"|"right"|"top"|"bottom"}. Returns the game after the move. Returns HTTP status 200 on success, 404 if the game is not found and 409 if the move is not legal in current game state.
    • DELETE request to /penkiolika/game/<id> - deletes the specified game and returns the deleted game.
    The <id> parameter in theese requests is an id of the game, which is returned every time a game is returned from the request, including on game's creation.

    A returned game follows the following JSON format: 

     
  {
      "id":<id>,
      "board":<game state>,
      "final":true|false
  }
    The <id> is a string value.
    The <game state> is an array of integers. It contains exactly 16 elements and the empty space is noted by the value 0. If the elements of the array are indexed starting 0, then the game board should be filled in the following order: 
     
   state[ 0] state[ 1] state[ 2] state[ 3]
   state[ 4] state[ 5] state[ 6] state[ 7]
   state[ 8] state[ 9] state[10] state[11]
   state[12] state[13] state[14] state[15]
    The "final" boolean parameter is true if and only if the game state is final. This means that the numbers in the bord are in consecutive order and that the empty space is in the bottom right corner of the board.

    The errors are returned as JSON objects {"reason":<reason>}, where <reason> is a string with error details.
